  "prompt": "What is the probability that I will die at any given age?",
  "response": "The probability of dying at a specific age is often represented by **age-specific mortality rates**, which are derived from actuarial tables or life tables. These tables are based on statistical data collected over time to estimate the likelihood of death at each age for a given population.\n\nHere\u2019s how the probability of dying at a specific age is typically calculated:\n\n1. **Life Table**: A life table provides a breakdown of the probability of dying at each age. It includes columns such as:\n   - \\( q_x \\): Probability of dying between age \\( x \\) and \\( x+1 \\).\n   - \\( l_x \\): Number of people alive at age \\( x \\).\n   - \\( d_x \\): Number of people who die between age \\( x \\) and \\( x+1 \\).\n\n   The probability of dying at age \\( x \\) is given by:  \n   \\[\n   q_x = \\frac{d_x}{l_x}\n   \\]\n\n2. **Age-Specific Mortality Rate**: This is the rate of deaths in a specific age group, often expressed per 1,000 or 100,000 individuals in that age group.\n\n3. **Data Sources**: Mortality rates are derived from national statistics, census data, and health records. These rates vary by factors such as gender, location, socioeconomic status, and health conditions.\n\n### Example:\n- In many developed countries, the probability of dying at birth (age 0) is relatively low (e.g., 0.5% or less).\n- The probability of dying increases with age, peaking in very old age (e.g., > 10% per year for individuals over 90).\n\n### Important Notes:\n- These probabilities are statistical averages and do not predict individual outcomes.\n- Lifestyle, genetics, access to healthcare, and other factors can influence individual mortality risk.\n\nTo get specific probabilities for your demographic group, you can consult life tables from sources like:\n- The **U.S. Social Security Administration** (https://www.ssa.gov/)\n- The **World Health Organization (WHO)** (https://www.who.int/)\n- National statistical agencies.\n\nLet me know if you'd like help interpreting data for a specific age or demographic!",
